segments.text: This is May 6th, I believe, and sitting in the very quiet and pleasant living room with Barney Welch and chatting with him about his years in College Station.
For someone who might listen to this or read it some years in the future and who might not know you,
Give a brief summary of your background before you came to A&M to be employed.
Where'd you grow up?
I was born in Eichel, Texas, September 3, 1922.
I moved from there at about three years old to Cleburne.
My father worked for J.C. Penney's.
This was in the middle of the 20s, right before the Depression hit.
The Depression came.
My dad moved to Stephenville, Texas, where I grew up.
I went to high school in Stephenville.
I was graduated at midterm, and I was not going to school until the fall.
I had a football scholarship to Rice University.
I didn't know anything about Rice.
I went to Houston and worked for Hughes Tools.
I was doing what they call parking lots.
They had split shifts in those days, and I would go out at 3 o'clock in the afternoon and park several hundred cars or direct parking in at night.
And I stayed there three or four months, and I got awfully homesick because I had never been away from home that far.
And one time I decided to see if I could leave, and I called a friend of mine named Darius Mosier at A&M who was a football player.
And I said, Darius, I don't like it down here.
And he said, well, get your butt up to East Texas.
So I went to Overton, Texas, and went to work for a man named Bert Fox, who was a class of 22, I think, who was doing almost all the work in those days.
Actually, we lived in New London, where they had a terrible explosion in 1937.
So I stayed there until...
school and then I came down to Texas A&M.
Alright, but keep going until you come here to be a... Oh, employee.
Okay, I came in 1941.
I came on the scholarship here.
We played in 41 and 42 and then all the basically fit sophomores were inducted as privates into the Army.
They had told us that
Being as we had two years of ROTC, we were chosen men, so we conducted as private and infantry.
And I left A&M in June of 43 and went to Camp Maxey, Texas, which is in Paris, Texas.
We were up there, took our basic training.
There were kids from what they called the 8th Corps area.
It was Oklahoma, Texas, Arkansas, Louisiana, and I don't know why.

We stayed there, took our basic, and then the Army said, we don't need all these guys right now, so they established what was called the ASTP, Army Reserve Training Program, Army Specialized Training Program.
So my group, about 300 or 400 of us, went to Commerce, Texas, and were learning and taking engineering, which I had not had.
I had been at ECO at A&M.
But I got some awfully good instruction, and we stayed there for several months, about four or five months.

Then the Army, the federal government decided they needed us, so we went back to Camp Maxey, took our training, and then shipped out to Europe in the infantry, where I spent about 30 months over there.
I was in the 99th Infantry Division.
I served in three different battles.
including Battle of the Balls and Remagen Bridge and some others.
After the war, in Europe, the way you came home was by points.
You had to have so many points.
If you were married, you had so many.
If you were so many months in service.
I happened to be married.
I had married just before I left to go into service.
But I had about nine months to spend in Europe.
And Patton happened to come through my
division one time and didn't think the military courtesy was good enough, so he sent a regiment of us down to Nuremberg, Germany, where the war tribunals were going to be held.
At that time, I had been transferred from the 99th to Big Red One, first in condition.
And we had 10,000 SS troopers under a stalag about six kilometers outside of Nuremberg, and every morning we would take all those guys into

Nuremberg, put 15, two and a half ton truck, would have guards in the front and back, and they would spend the day cleaning up the debris that Nuremberg had suffered when we actually fought in Nuremberg.
What happened, we couldn't take Nuremberg, so somebody pulled us back and they bombed it and shelled it real heavy.
But then, after that, I came home and I shipped out of Marseille, France, Christmas Eve, 1945,
and was discharged at Tyler, Texas in 1946.
And that was January, so I still had some time before I got back to A&M, and I worked just during day labor there at Stephenville until we came back to A&M in 1946.
All right, and then you came as a student, graduated.
I came back as a junior.
At that time, there were no motels, no hotels, except on the campus that had one was called
Aggieland Inn?
Aggieland Inn, yeah.
Well, a guy named Pinky Downs, who's quite a famous Aggie, who at that time was the ticket agent for the football, I mean, athletic department.
He got me an apartment in Bryan.
My wife and I had a little boy that was three years old.
We lived there for a few months, and then I moved to a place called Blue Top Courts out to Eastgate.
And we stayed there for...

several months, and then Mr. Gilchrist, who was president, bought a bunch of army barracks from Victoria, Texas, moved them up here a little bit north of the campus called College View, and as we finished one, it let some people move in.
You moved in according to your day of graduation, and they took each one of these barracks and made four apartments of it.
They had a little
with two little bedrooms, a living and dining room, and a little kitchen.
And we moved into there, paying $28 a month.
And there was lots of us.
We were all in the same boat.
Nobody had any money.
We had about $90 a month from the GI Bill.
And because I was on scholarships, I was better than most of them.
And we lived there.
And I went ahead and played two more years of ball.
One summer, the last year that I was in school, I was up in Pine intramurals softball for a guy named Spike White, who at that time was director of student activities under Mr. Pemberton.
He was dean of men.
And Spike asked me, when I was about to graduate and make terms, I'd be interested in taking over the intramural department, which he had until he moved up to director of student activities.
27, I guess, then, and had a child and jumped at that.
And I had the opportunity to play pro ball, but I didn't think I could make it because I'd been at it too long.
I didn't think I was good enough first place.
All right, so you go on the payroll then as a full-time employee.
And when was that, 47?
That was January, no, January of 48.
And do you remember what your starting pay was?
$2,400 for 12 months.
12 months.
And in general, describe your duties as director of intramural.
Well, for the people who do not know, intramural means within, of course.
And this was a program that was strictly for the students.
At that time, they were all boys here, and there was nothing else in this community.
There was no night clubs, no eating places, no girls.
There was nothing for these jokers to do.
So we had a very strong intramural program.
We had, at that time, the core outfits.
A infantry would play B infantry and so forth and so forth.
And we had about, oh, I don't know, 30, 40 sports they could participate in, like football and basketball and horseshoes and tennis and all that stuff.
And that was my responsibility to oversee that program, to schedule it, to direct it.
I didn't have any help, and that was Secretary didn't have anything.
Of course, we even saved old nails out of boards to use them on.
The only money we got was from that.
from the exchange store money.
We had an exchange store, as you know.
And they declared profits each year, and they supported a lot of student activities.
And intramurals got, I don't remember, like $70,000, $80,000 a year, maybe a little bit more to operate that program.
That's probably what it was.
All right, and where did intramural games and contests largely take place?
On the campus.
No, but where?
Physically.
Okay.
Behind Duncan Messall, which is now called Duncan Drillfield, we had softball fields there.
The basketball was at the Grove, and we used some of D-wear when we could get in.
After they built G. Roddy White, we used part of it upstairs there.
The rifle was under the stadium.
Softball was on the field, as I said.
We had a football, we had five football fields south of Kyle Field that were strictly intramurals.
There hadn't been parking for football, but we finally got to put a chain around it so we could keep it nice and clean and so forth.
Were there any sports that y'all included that today would be considered a little unusual?
Like y'all didn't play field hockey, you didn't play... No, we didn't play hockey, we didn't play any of those, what we call, we didn't play soccer.
It was the thing that we played in high school.
And didn't play horseshoes.
We did horseshoes.
Oh, you did horseshoes.
We had a great horseshoe program.
And we had a bowling program once the MSC was built.
We had a ping pong program.
We had golf.
Polo was gone.
Polo was gone.
That was when I was a sophomore.
And do you have any idea how many students...
participated in interviews.
At that time, after the war, when I left here in 43, I think, when I came back, it was terrible.
We had 9,000 kids.
Now, they weren't all core.
We had two programs there.
Then we had the military and what we called the non-reg, the civilians.
And the civilians played, but they were not as competitive or as...
intent as the Corps was, in order to get the George Moore flag, which is the top board you can get at Texas A&M, you had to have some intramural points.

So they really played, not only they played intramural because they liked it, because they were young and they enjoyed working out, plus there was nothing else to do, they also wanted some George Moore.
Does that trophy go way back?
Well, I understand George Moore was at Corregidor getting more.
Oh, so...
So he must have been back in...
But where the trophy came from, it was here when I got here.
Okay.
And was there...
I've heard that there was a great deal of prestige connected with winning that trophy.
Oh, very much.
We made a big deal out of it.
Was there any outfit that was regularly the winner?
The infantry won it eight years ago.
Infantry won it?
Well, just for eight years, I know.
Why?
What did they do?
They wouldn't recruit.
Mm-hmm.
Now I don't know if you remember, or you know about it, whoever's going to hear this, but Hazen was terribly bad after we came back after the war.
Really got terribly bad.
Mainly because the kids were, they hadn't gone through it themselves and they didn't know what it was all about.
It got so bad that the kids were moved to Annex, remember?
So they had their own, we had our own separate program for them out there.
So some of the units on campus would go recruit
These kids out there, it's like you're doing football.
And they find the athletes and they bring them in.
Well, they actually just worked that hard the rest of them did.
I see.
Did you, were you responsible for the intramurals out at the annex?
Yes, but a guy named Luke Harrison took care of it.
I think he was, you know Luke.
He kind of ran them, but it all came under my program.
But I didn't actually go out there like I did on the campus.
All right, now these folks that you mentioned, Spike White,
describe him.
Okay, he's probably the best friend I ever had.
His boss was a guy named Penberthy.
Yes, yes.
Mr. Penberthy at that time was the most loved man probably ever on this campus.
He came here in 1924, I think, from Ohio State, and he started the intramural program and the physical education program and ran it.
About 1937, Spike was graduating from A&M, and he
He was an electrical engineer and worked in Dallas, Texas, but he didn't like that.
He wanted to be in the recreation.
So he came back and got a degree in recreation at Mr. Penberthy.
Asked him to take over the annual program, which he did.
Then Mike went to the Navy during the war.
And then when he came back, before the war, we did not have a dean of men here at Texas A&M commanding everything.
There was a guy named...
Who was the first one?
Went on to East Texas to coach football.
I don't know.
I'll come back.
We had one man who was made dean of men, but he had had a run-in with one of the board of regents early, back in the early years, and they got rid of him.
And I can't thank Samuel O'Neill.
So then they asked Mr. Penberthy to become dean of men, and it's my understanding that Mr. Gilchrist and some others asked
begged him or encouraged him not to take it.
When he was dean of men, he had responsibility for all the discipline but no control over the Corps.
So he became the bad guy.
He's one that had to kick him out of school.
And going from the greatest man that probably ever came to Texas at that time, he became one of the most disliked.
He was even ridiculed in the battalion, which is under his role in being this guy.
But anyway, Spike was the guy that built up the golf course here at Texas A&M.
Spike built the rodeo arena, which is now where Olsen Field is.
Spike really built up all the dances, the graduations, all that stuff with understudent activities.
He, well, I don't know.
He was one of the finest men.
He was one of the finest men, I guess I would say.
But he later, what he's really done since then, he bought a boys camp in Branson, Missouri in 1954 called Candy Cup Camp for Boys, which had originally belonged to Dope Walker's father in the 1920s.
Really?
Dope Walker's daddy would take kids from Dallas down there.
We're talking about his money.
Take them down there and work out.
Then a man named Bill Lance, who was a track coach at Tulsa Central, took it over.
Mm-hmm.
And Spike bought it in 54.
Well, in 55, my wife and I went up there with Spike.
We had 60 boys, and we kept them for eight weeks.
We had little boys.
We had captains one through 12.
We kept them for eight weeks.
Some of these kids were like nine years old.
I doubt if many parents would turn a nine-year-old into somebody for eight weeks.
Last year, 1998, that camp had
15,000, which had become a Boys and Girls camp.
It's the largest Boys and Girls Christian camp in the world, I guess.
I know in Missouri, many, many students were really impressed that I knew about the camp and knew the whites.
We had guys, women, girls and boys flying in from Spain, from South America.
We had Edward Sennacher, Tom Landers, grandkids, you name any great
Outstanding person in this United States, and they probably got somebody to thank too.
All right, let's go back for a minute to both Mr. Penberthy and Mr. White.
What made them such special people?
What were their qualities?
Give some examples.
They were Christians.
Okay.
That's the main thing.
Okay.
And they liked people.
Now, Doe Raleigh, this guy was trying, Doe was the first one.
Mr. Penberthy was always, if I had to compare anybody to St. Paul, I'd pick him.
Okay.
He can't, of course.
But I'll tell you an example of Spike.
After Spike got his degree in electrical engineering, he went out to California to work on a master's.
He worked in a foundry at night to go to school.
And you know what kind of people he was.
He took his Aggie ring off because he didn't want those people to think he was better than me.
That's what kind of guy he was.
I've never known a man...
Spike, every night, he'd get down on his knees and pray.
Thanks to God for taking care of him.
They're just Christian men.
They never talked, but they lived a Christian life.
Plus, they were interested in young men.
I don't know.
If you've got that, you can do anything.
Right now, intramurals reported to Spike.
Spike reported to Pembroke.
Mr. Penberthy reported to the president?
Okay.
Now, Mr. Penberthy was dean of men, and they had two branches, student activities and student affairs.
Benny Zinn was head of student affairs.
The back was head of student activities.
This all came about after the war.
Benny Zinn had everything pertaining to the college, the police, the mess halls, stuff.

all this back at everything else presently give you a crisp yet described back up a little bit what i know that he played became a very different he was texas he came here i think in nineteen thirty seven and
I understand this, and I can't prove it, you probably know, but he's responsible for the Goldside Park and for planting the flowers in Texas.
That I believe is true.
And he was president, and what I loved about that man, I was on a couple of little small committees, he would call a meeting, and he did not go away from the agenda.
If we're going to be there five minutes, he started time, and he quit.
We didn't talk football.
We didn't talk about religion.
We didn't talk politics.
He stepped to the agenda, kept to the agenda.
Once this time was up, then you could do whatever you wanted to.
But he was very, very organized and a very honest man.
I went to see him after he retired.
In fact, he lived right behind this back over here.
And I'd go out and visit.
We'd talk and all.
He said, you know, I don't think he was complaining.
He said, you know, hardly anybody ever comes to me.
He was the president.
And you know as well as I do that A&M is a cold-blooded organization.
It can be.
It can be very cold-blooded.
Now, his son about your age was... No, he was a little bit under his son's name, Henry Gilchrist.
He's a lawyer in Dallas with a big law firm.
Were you...
When the students marched on the president's house about hazing, were you back when that occurred?
I got involved in it when it went away.
You want me to tell you that story?
Yes.
I lived in College U.
We worked out football, and I was walking home and happened to go through what at that time was the assembly hall, where we used to have free movies on Saturday night.
And it was right across the street from Preston's home, and I walked by, and there was this huge crowd of people in there.
Being curious, I walked in there, and they were having a meeting about Gilchrist.
And a lot of the state radio networks, I don't have any words, were here.
And one guy got up in Clinton, but he knew that Gilchrist went every weekend down on the coast to a ship and took women out.
Another said that he was absconding with funds from the exchange store and the wind tunnel.
I've never been in a mall back and forth.
It was horrible, just terrible.
Everybody cheered.
Nobody didn't even know who Gil Gilchrist was.
Colonel Frank Anderson, another great guy here, who at one time had been commandant with dear friend of Gil, came out on the stage, like I say now, had on his uniform.
He was not military at that time.
He was practical.
He came out on the stage in full military and tried to talk to defend Gil Gilchrist.
It was horrible.
I later apologized to Gibb because I didn't, I said I didn't have enough guts to stand up and defend you.
And I was just like, okay, I'll sit down and listen.
As you know, the Corps marched on his home at midnight with the band.
And he didn't even give them the courtesy to come to the front door, which I really admired.
Gibb Gilchrist, between College Station and Hearn, there is an underpass over a railroad track.

And he used to be criticized severely because the road that's going to Highway 6 is going down this direction, north, and then it veers a little bit northwest and goes around back to north and goes on through.
And they said that he built this crooked road under that railroad crossing.
But it turns out the state law requires that all undercrosses have to be a 90-degree angle.
But he was criticized worse than Mr. Pemberthy was in the battalions.
And primarily, I think it was because he went to Texas University.
Well, and also, wasn't he trying to terminate all, some of that hazing?
Yeah, he, well, yeah, everybody's talking.
Yes, he was.
In fact, I don't know if this is true or not, but I heard at the time that we came within one or two votes to lose McCord from the state congressman because of hazing.
And the hazing was terrible.
Now, the hazing was bad when I was here
But people don't really understand.
We didn't think it was bad.
What was bad, when we as sophomores left here, left kids who had never gone through the Hazen program in charge, and they just went wild.
They would march attention to Herndon, Texas.
Sure.
They'd stand them up at attention in the showers.
When I was in the murals, I'd be walking down Joe Brout Boulevard and see these upper class and take these freshmen standing there and
Screaming and hollering at them and blowing smoke in their face.
Wouldn't even let them go to class.
And I'd get right in the middle of it.
It got that bad.
It got away from this fun thing of busting your butt to this thing of mental haste, which is so bad.
All right, so now you directed intramurals for how long?
Until 1961.
61, so... Then I left.
So 15?
Well, from 48 to...
Eight, 11, 13 years.
13 years.
When you left Intramurals, what changes were there?
Me or them?
Them.
Well, today people still think I work at A&M.
I've lived here 57 years.
And I don't know.
A&M to me is where it's changed.
It's kind of like your children you were talking about.
You're with them.
so much when they're little, and that you don't notice these gradual little changes as they get older.
Now, the Aggies that come back, been gone 15 years, they come back, see this campus, they can't believe it.
But when you grow up with it, you don't pay attention to it.
But changes, the Corps was the same, the civilians were the same.
The Corps was losing more of its advantage, I think, used to, whenever a Corps kid ran for office, he was going to win it, take a yellow and stuff like that.
Civilians come in.
But in 61, had you all changed the number of sports involved?
Are you talking about the intramural?
Yeah.
No, no, they stayed the same.
They're still today.
Today they're so much bigger than we were then.
Your facilities were about the same?
The facilities kept going the same until just after the girls got here.
The girls changed things.
Right, let's see.
Then in terms of leadership, Spike left.
Who replaced him?
being a student.
Well, that's when MSC opened up, seeing all that moved over there, when Wayne Stark took over.
Now, your friend, Charles McCann, took my job.
Charles worked for me when he was a student, a dollar an hour.
And when I decided to leave to go into insurance business, they...
Mr. Petey asked me, could you recommend?
And I said, well, there's only one guy that can do it.
He's ever been around.
It's Charles McKenna.
He's in school down here.
He came on up here, and he later became a provost.
He took it, and a guy named Les Palmer took it, and some others.
But I used to get awfully unhappy when I had intramurals that nobody would come down and watch it from the campus.
I said, man, that's the greatest thing we've got on this world.
Nope.
I'd call Mr. Gilkerson.
He'd come down.
Mr.
Rudder would come down sometime.
Then, you know, I left.
I've never been back over there.
Never have seen him again.
During your era, who else had an intramural program similar to A&M's?
Texas and Ohio State probably had the two greatest.
I went to a convention one time.
They were way ahead of us.
They ran a little differently.

procedures but Texas probably had a better not better but equal to us but they had more selfies and Ohio State was claimed most to say they had the greatest they probably did right in that 13 years more kids began to get automobiles and so forth but did the participation rate remain it did in the course
because it was kind of compulsory.
The civilians was not, but it kept up, but the civilians did not keep up with the Corps.
For example, we had two of everything.
We had a freshman football team and an up-class football team.
We had a freshman basketball team.
Each outfit had to have two seats, so we got every one of the kids like that.
They didn't have a lot of choice for anything, particularly in wrestling, boxing, and those things, so we finally cut those out.
All right, now let's see.
Mr. Penberthy...
He held that job.
I don't remember how long.
A long time.
Yeah, and what happened there?
I don't know.
Did he got shafted?
Was he replaced by Hennigan?
No, yes, I think.
Let me tell you what happened without going into why.
This man in 1924 or whatever came here and started this thing from scratch.
He was head of the PE department when he left and went to being a man, which a lot of people didn't want him to.
After he left being a man, he went back to the PE department as an instructor in volleyball because he needed to finish out his tenure to get his retirement.
He even went to, and I didn't know this while he told me this, he went to California to learn about volleyball.
And he came back to hear Carl Landis.
and Carl Tishler were running a program who he had hired, and he was a little peon for us raising to it and working.
Not many men could do that.
That's right.
And never, ever has he ever criticized that.
Right.
All right, let's see.
Did you have any relationship with President Morgan?
No.
Because I don't find many people that remember him and have many comments about him.
All right, when President Rutter comes in 59, did he have any interest in intramurals, as you recall?
Yeah, well, of course, that wasn't his agenda, but I told you this morning, Earl Coates at Carlton State in 1939-40, when I was senior high school, and that's when I first met him.
Now, we weren't buddy-buddies, because he was just a rural Rutter in the last 32 years.
But when he came down here, my daughter happened to be the same age as his two daughters, and they went to school together.
My nephew and Bob, Bud, his son, were roommates here when they were friends.
Oh, really?
So, and Margaret and I were good friends.
We all went to Method Church for a place, and Pinky Downs was there, you know.
Yeah.
But Earl was, I didn't see him a lot, but.
I've got some letters in there he's written me, and I like everybody else.
Somebody says, I think we need a dormitory just to house all his roommates, and that's what I'm doing.
But, yes, if I wanted something, I didn't go to him, certainly, but he would talk to me, and we were on...
